# Part 1

### Explain what a p-value is and how a researcher should use it. (150 words or less)

A p-value is the probability of obtaining a test statistic as extreme as or more extreme than the one observed, assuming the null hypothesis is true. A p-value is used to evaluate how consistent the observed data are with the null hypothesis. Researchers use the p-value to guide their conclusions in hypothesis testing by comparing it to a chosen significance level. If the p-value is small, the observed result would be unlikely under the null hypothesis, which may lead the researcher to reject the null hypothesis.The article we read about p-hacking cautions against the use of a p-value and its significance in repeatedly running models, choosing data until a statistically significant outcome surfaces. Therefore, researchers must avoid selectively presenting only statistically significant results and producing misleading conclusions. 


# Part 2

## Randomization test for numeric data

```{r}
# Data credit: David C. Howell
# `no_waiting` is a vector that records the time it took a driver to leave the 
# parking spot if no one was waiting for the driver
no_waiting <- c(36.30, 42.07, 39.97, 39.33, 33.76, 33.91, 39.65, 84.92, 40.70, 39.65,
39.48, 35.38, 75.07, 36.46, 38.73, 33.88, 34.39, 60.52, 53.63, 50.62)

# `waiting` is a vector that records the time it takes a driver to leave if
# someone was waiting on the driver
waiting <- c(49.48, 43.30, 85.97, 46.92, 49.18, 79.30, 47.35, 46.52, 59.68, 42.89,
49.29, 68.69, 41.61, 46.81, 43.75, 46.55, 42.33, 71.48, 78.95, 42.06)

mean(waiting)
mean(no_waiting)
obs_dif <- mean(waiting) - mean(no_waiting)
```

### Randomization test

```{r}
all_times <- c(waiting, no_waiting)

set.seed(1)

k <- 10000
diffs <- numeric(k)

for(i in 1:k){
  
  shuffled <- sample(all_times)
  
  group1 <- shuffled[1:20]
  group2 <- shuffled[21:40]
  
  diffs[i] <- mean(group1) - mean(group2)
  
}

p_value <- sum(diffs >= obs_dif) / k
p_value


```

The randomized test produced a p value of approximately 0.0193. Since the p value is less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis.
As such, there seems to be statistically significant evidence that drivers take longer to leave their parking spaces when they know someone is waiting for them.

### Comparison to traditional t-test

Conduct a traditional two-sample independent t-test.

```{r}
t.test(waiting, no_waiting,
                        alternative = "greater",
                        var.equal = FALSE)
```
The p value from the two sample t test was similar to that of the randomized test. Since the p-value (0.019) is less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis.
There is statistically significant evidence that drivers take longer to leave a parking space when someone is waiting than when no one is waiting.


