# Part 4

Let 𝑝ECMO be the survival probability with ECMO and 𝑝CMT be the probability of survival for conventional therapy 

H0: 𝑝ECMO = 𝑝CMT
HA: 𝑝ECMO > 𝑝CMT
### Randomization test

Perform a randomization test

```{r}

set.seed(1)

# TRUE = lived, FALSE = died
outcome_ecmo <- c(rep(TRUE,6), rep(FALSE,4),
                  rep(TRUE,28), rep(FALSE,1))

treatment_ecmo <- c(rep("CMT",10), rep("ECMO",29))

obs_diff_ecmo <- mean(outcome_ecmo[treatment_ecmo == "ECMO"]) -
                 mean(outcome_ecmo[treatment_ecmo == "CMT"])

obs_diff_ecmo

k_ecmo <- 10000
diffs_ecmo <- numeric(k_ecmo)

for (i in 1:k_ecmo) {
  shuffled_treatment_ecmo <- sample(treatment_ecmo)
  
  diffs_ecmo[i] <- mean(outcome_ecmo[shuffled_treatment_ecmo == "ECMO"]) -
                   mean(outcome_ecmo[shuffled_treatment_ecmo == "CMT"])
}

p_value_ecmo <- sum(diffs_ecmo >= obs_diff_ecmo) / k_ecmo
p_value_ecmo

```

The empirical p-value was p =  0.0117. Since the p-value 0.0117 < 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis.n the context of this study, this result indicates that the survival rates for newborn babies treated with ECMO are not the same as those treated with conventional medical therapy.


### Comparison to Fisher's Exact Test

Use R's `fisher.test()` 

```{r}
ecmo_table <- matrix(c(6, 4,
                       28, 1),
                     nrow = 2,
                     byrow = TRUE)

colnames(ecmo_table) <- c("Live", "Die")
rownames(ecmo_table) <- c("CMT", "ECMO")

ecmo_table

fisher.test(ecmo_table, alternative = "less")
```

Using Fisher’s exact test with the same hypotheses, the p-value was 0.01102, which is very similar to the empirical p-value of 0.0117 from the randomization test. Both p-values are below 0.05, so both methods lead to rejecting the null hypothesis. In context, the survival rates for newborn babies treated with ECMO are not the same as those treated with conventional medical therapy.

# Part 5

## _Comparing Groups, Chapter 7, Exercise 7.1_

### Non-parametric bootstrap test
Under the null hypothesis that the group variances are equal, both groups are assumed to come from the same population distribution, so bootstrap samples are drawn from the pooled science scores to simulate the distribution of the variance difference when the null hypothesis is true. Alternatively, I considered resampling each group seperately -- preserving the original group variances. Based on the slides from lecture as well as general assumption, I chose to use the pooled resampling approach.  

```{r}
hsb <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/zief0002/comparing-groups/master/data/HSB.csv")

head(hsb)

#according to codebook, 0 = private, 1 = public
sci_public  <- hsb$Sci[hsb$Schtyp == 1]
sci_private <- hsb$Sci[hsb$Schtyp == 0]

# Observed difference in variances
obs_diff <- var(sci_public) - var(sci_private)

# Sample sizes
n_pub  <- length(sci_public)
n_priv <- length(sci_private)

# Bootstrap setup
set.seed(1)
k <- 10000
boot_diffs <- numeric(k)

# Combined scores (pooled under H0)
pooled_scores <- hsb$Sci

for(i in 1:k){
  
  boot_pub  <- sample(pooled_scores, size = n_pub, replace = TRUE)
  boot_priv <- sample(pooled_scores, size = n_priv, replace = TRUE)
  
  boot_diffs[i] <- var(boot_pub) - var(boot_priv)
}

# Empirical p-value
p_value <- mean(abs(boot_diffs) >= abs(obs_diff))
p_value
```

The non-parametric bootstrap test with 10,000 resamples produced an empirical p-value of 0.1063. Since this is greater than 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis at the 5% significance level. In context, the data do not provide evidence that the variability of science scores differs between public and private school students.

### Parametric bootstrap test

Use a parametric bootstrap test

```{r}
set.seed(1)
# sample sizes
n_pub <- length(sci_public)
n_priv <- length(sci_private)

# observed difference in variances
diff_schtyp <- var(sci_public) - var(sci_private)

# pooled variance under H0
var_equal <- var(c(sci_public, sci_private))
# group means
mean_pub <- mean(sci_public)
mean_priv <- mean(sci_private)
# number of bootstrap simulations
k <- 10000
boot_var_diff <- numeric(k)
for(i in 1:k){

  sim_pub <- rnorm(n_pub, mean = mean_pub, sd = sqrt(var_equal))
  sim_priv <- rnorm(n_priv, mean = mean_priv, sd = sqrt(var_equal))

  boot_var_diff[i] <- var(sim_pub) - var(sim_priv)
}

# empirical p-value
p_value_param <- sum(abs(boot_var_diff) >= abs(diff_schtyp)) / k
p_value_param
```

Assumption: We assume that science scores follow a Normal distribution within each school type. Under H0, the variances are equal, so both groups use the same variance. 

H0: σ^2 public = σ^2 private
HA: σ^2 public not = σ^2 private

The empirical p-value from 10,000 simulated samples was 0.1619. Since this p-value is greater than 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. In context, the data do not indicate that the variability of science scores differs between public and private school students.

