```{r}
light <- c(28, 26, 33, 24, 34,-44, 27, 16, 40, -2, 29, 22, 24, 21, 25, 30, 23, 29, 31, 19,
           24, 20, 36, 32, 36, 28, 25, 21, 28, 29, 37, 25, 28, 26, 30, 32, 36, 26, 30, 22, 
           36, 23, 27, 27, 28, 27, 31, 27, 26, 33, 26, 32, 32, 24, 39, 28, 24, 25, 32, 25, 
           29, 27, 28, 29, 16, 23)
```

### Non-parametric bootstrap test

Perform a bootstrap test

```{r}
set.seed(1)

# observed statistic
sample_mean_light <- mean(light)

# shift data so mean = 33 under H0
light_null_population <- light + (33 - sample_mean_light)

# bootstrap settings
num_bootstrap <- 100000
bootstrap_means <- numeric(num_bootstrap)

for(i in 1:num_bootstrap){

  bootstrap_sample <- sample(light_null_population,
                             size = length(light_null_population),
                             replace = TRUE)

  bootstrap_means[i] <- mean(bootstrap_sample)
}

# empirical p-value
p_value_light <- sum(abs(bootstrap_means - 33) >=
                     abs(sample_mean_light - 33)) / num_bootstrap

p_value_light
```
The p value is very small: 5e-05. Interpretation below. 

### Non-parametric bootstrap test with outliers removed

Perform the bootstrap test again after removing the two negative outliers (-2, and -44) 

```{r}
# remove outliers
light_no_outliers <- light[light != -44 & light != -2]

# new observed mean
sample_mean_no_outliers <- mean(light_no_outliers)

# shift sample so mean = 33 under H0
light_null_population_no_outliers <-
  light_no_outliers + (33 - sample_mean_no_outliers)

num_bootstrap <- 100000
bootstrap_means_no_outliers <- numeric(num_bootstrap)

for(i in 1:num_bootstrap){

  bootstrap_sample_no_outliers <-
    sample(light_null_population_no_outliers,
           size = length(light_null_population_no_outliers),
           replace = TRUE)

  bootstrap_means_no_outliers[i] <- mean(bootstrap_sample_no_outliers)
}

# empirical p-value
p_value_no_outliers <-
  sum(abs(bootstrap_means_no_outliers - 33) >=
      abs(sample_mean_no_outliers - 33)) / num_bootstrap

p_value_no_outliers

```


Explain why the p-value is even smaller: 

A non-parametric bootrap test was used to see if Newcomb’s measurements are significantly different from the modern
accepted value of 33. The sample was shifted so that the bootstrap population had mean 33 under the null hypothesis. The empirical p-value was extremely small, so we reject the null hypothesis. Removing the outliers greatly reduces the variability of the data. This makes the bootstrap sampling distribution of the mean much narrower under the null hypothesis. Because the distribution is narrower, a mean of 27.75 becomes more extreme relative to that distribution, even though it is closer to 33 than 26.21 was. Therefore the p-value becomes even smaller. In context, the data suggest that the mean of Newcomb’s measurements may differ from the modern accepted value of 33 nanoseconds.






